[MEDIA] Completed with 3 findings:
  > Rationale: The adverse media screening for Olo Inc. (Olo) reveals several notable legal and corporate governance issues, though none represent critical breaking news that fundamentally alters the risk profile to an extreme level. The most significant findings include: 1) A $9 million class action shareholder settlement preliminarily approved in 2024/2025 regarding allegations that Olo misrepresented its active restaurant locations and failed to disclose the termination of its partnership with Subway. 2) Ongoing fiduciary duty investigations by multiple law firms (such as Bleichmar Fonti & Auld LLP and DJS Law Group) initiated in mid-2025 regarding Olo's pending $2 billion acquisition by Thoma Bravo, focusing on whether the board acted in the best interest of shareholders and the high concentration of voting power (82%) held by insiders. 3) A historical contract and fraud dispute with DoorDash that was settled in 2021. The shareholder settlement and the ongoing fiduciary investigations represent medium-severity risks due to their recent timeline and relevance to corporate governance and transparency.
  > Raw Data: {"query":"Olo news scandal controversy lawsuit investigation","results":[{"title":"OLO SEC Filings - Olo Inc 10-K, 10-Q, 8-K Forms","source_url":"https://www.stocktitan.net/sec-filings/OLO/","content":"Olo Inc. (OLO) has undergone a corporate status transition, culminating in a merger where Olo beca...
  - [MEDIUM] Olo Inc. reached a preliminary $9 million class action settlement to resolve shareholder allegations that the company and its executives made false and misleading statements regarding its business metrics and failed to disclose the impending termination of its partnership with Subway restaurants.
  - [MEDIUM] Multiple law firms (including BFA Law and DJS Law Group) are actively investigating Olo Inc., its board of directors, and CEO Noah H. Glass for potential breaches of fiduciary duties related to the company's pending $2 billion acquisition by Thoma Bravo, highlighting concerns over shareholder fairness and concentrated insider voting power.
  - [LOW] Olo resolved a high-profile contract and fraud lawsuit with DoorDash in 2021, which involved allegations of overcharging and violating most-favored-nation clauses, resulting in a multi-year partnership agreement and a $25 million letter of credit.
